===Glyph origin===
{{Han etym}}
{{Han compound|巾|t1=cloth|冒|ls=psc|c1=s|c2=p}}. Originally written as {{och-l|*冃}}; later, {{och-l|*目}} and {{och-l|*巾}} were added.

===Etymology===
Wanderwort of Southeastern and Eastern Asia, thus its origin is disputed.

Possibly from {{der|zh|sit}}. It has been compared to {{cog|bo|རྨོག||helmet}} (Starostin; {{zh-ref|Sagart, 2017}}) and {{cog|sit-rgy}} forms for “mushroom” (cf. {{noncog|br|tog-touseg}}, literally “frog hat”), such as {{cog|sit-jap|tɤ'''jmɤɣ'''}} ({{zh-ref|Zhang, Jacques and Lai, 2019}}). Following this etymology, {{inh|zh|sit-pro|*lmuk}} is reconstructible.

Alternatively, {{zh-ref|Schuessler (2007)}} suggests an {{der|zh|aav}} derivation since this is a relatively late word and ''{{w|Shuowen}}'' defines {{zh-l|*冃}} (an ancient form of {{lang|zh|帽}}) as “head cover” of the Southern [[蠻夷|indigenous]] people, which may allude to a southern origin. Compare {{cog|mkh-pro|*muuk|*muuk ~ muək|hat}}, whence {{cog|mnw|ဒမှော်|tr=həmok||wide hat}} and {{cog|km|មួក}}, which he also connects to {{och-l|鍪|metal cap; helmet}}. Also compare {{cog|th|หมวก}}, which {{zh-ref|Schuessler (2007)}} derives from the Khmer word. However, {{zh-ref|Alves (2018)}} considers it likely for the Proto-Mon-Khmer word to be a loan from Chinese, and {{zh-ref|Alves (2020)}} also suggests that the Tai forms spread from Chinese.

Often considered to be related to {{och-l|冒|to cover|id=1}} ({{zh-ref|Wang, 1982}}; Starostin), though {{zh-ref|Schuessler (2007)}} thinks that it may be reinterpreted as such based on parallel development of {{och-l|被|to cover; bedding}}.

